photo.title: Municipal Of Gold

description._content: Beautiful San Francisco, California from the top of the Coit Tower.  It was your typical hot and hazy summer day in the Bay Area, and if I knew then what I definitely know now, I would have tried to arrive here a bit earlier in the day.  This was before my complete understanding of adjusting your trip plans for photography.  I was always under the impression that I could just be there and show up whenever I want and get the picture I want.  How silly and naive J-Ri was!  This was also before I purchased my tripod that I always use, pretty good for handheld.  Looking back I don't know if you could use a tripod up in the tower though, you would get reflections from the windows.  One thing I remember about handheld photography is people tend to stare at you a little less.  The minute I grab my tripod, get it out and start extending it, yes that's correct, staring 101.  Anyway, we have some tone mapping going on, this image needed a little kick, I really enjoy it, it definitely breaks through the haze.  Eventually my skyline collection will rival my waterfall collection, I just have to get out and around the country.  It would be kind of nice if Seattle weren't so isolated.  Alright, I'm rambling a bit.  Thanks so much for checking this out.  Enjoy!

photo.title: Holiday Stars

description._content:
I am so disappointed!!! After two days of rain, the San Francisco sky opened up on Monday with beautiful fish scale patterned clouds at dusk. This could well be the last chance before NYE to catch the holiday lights at Embarcadero. I had planned to arrived shortly before sunset to set up and look around for good shooting angles. But we got stuck in traffic, watching the gorgeous rosy hues across the sky gradually fading away while stomping our feet in futile frustration. Alas, having relaxed through this UCSF holiday, we forgot it’s a normal commute day for most of the city and rush hour traffic should have been factored into the logistics. We didn’t arrive until 5:30pm, barely catching the tail end of blue hour. The best lighting was already GONE baby GONE!

I would like to have the Transamerica Pyramid positioned a bit more toward the center, like the shot below in the Comments. But from this spot I couldn’t position the pyramid at 1/3 while including all four of the Embarcadero Center towers (and the OCD part of me insisted on having all four towers in my shot). Moving further back might have helped, but there were people behind me and I didn’t want them to pop into the frame. As the last bit of blue disappeared from the sky, I just gave up obsessing. Well, life is never perfect, is it? =)

photo.title: I live here.

description._content: Well, maybe not here here. Here here, in this photo, is Treasure Island. In short, i live here:SF. I took this shot (these shots - it's in two pieces and the gap is beyond obvious, which I didn't notice when I was editing it this morning. Sleepy!) at the tail-end of my ILHSF photoshoot with Julie. Clearly, all y'all local folks are familiar with it, but for those of you who aren't in the Bay Area here is Julie's description of the project. Even though I live in the Mission, I knew right away that I would want to do it on Treasure Island. It's my happy place. One of the few complaints I have about living in the city is that I don't get out there as much. No one else done their shoot on TI at that point, so I figured if anyone would be the one to show it love, it'd be me. The week of the shoot had been unseasonably hot (which I love), but I wanted fog and gloom - it just seemed more SF appropriate. It ended up - to my delight - being gray when we started over the bridge that morning. Eventually, we got this. That sky was the perfect backdrop. The shoot itself was so much fun. I got to put on my favorite shoes and favorite dress and scamper all over one of my favorite favorite places in the Bay. I think my experience was different from many who participate because I met Julie long before doing the shoot. Even if that hadn't been the case, I'm sure I would have felt instantly comfortable with her. One of the things that's so great about the project is the way that Julie is able to coax people out of camera shyness and really connect - which is so essential in portraiture. (Or you could just shoot hams - like me - I suppose.) It feels official now. I am a San Franciscan, whatever that means. Thank you, Julie. And thank you, San Francisco, for loving me back every now and then.

photo.title: Transamerica Pyramid

description._content: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transamerica_Pyramid Since its completion in 1972, the Transamerica Pyramid has become one of the most recognized buildings in the United States. It's distinctive shape dominates the San Francisco skyline and is visible from most parts of town. To many people, it is an icon of San Francisco on par with the Golden Gate Bridge or the city's famous cable cars. The 48-story office tower, designed by William Pereira & Associates, stretches 853 feet above the street and is topped by a 212-foot needle-shaped spire. The spire is lit from within and seems to glow once evening falls. The change in the building's dimensions as it rises from the street is dramatic: each of the lower floors offer 22,000 square feet of space while the floors at the top have a mere 45 square feet.

photo.title: To lay me down in silence easy.

description._content: PX600 + ND Pack Filter (Two stops? One stop? Not really sure. I should find out about that.) After a bit of a struggle with overexposure and overheating, I finally - on the last three shots of the pack - figured out PX600. And I love it. The tones are so gorgeous. The slight yellow tint to it is very up my alley. I prefer it to PX100, but since the only stuff of that I've shot is FF, I suppose it's to be expected. But the contrast certainly seems better, the shadows richer. Someone asked me why I sometimes do and sometimes don't crop my 'Roids. Not sure if I've mentioned why, so: sometimes a frame looks nice. Sometimes it doesn't. Simple as that. Oh, and if I write on the border, I like to keep that uncropped. And please note that I never use fake Polaroid borders on digital shots. I'm all about digital fakery... but there's something sacred about Polaroids. Recently, I started writing what amounts to EXIF data on the back. It's very useful for that, but sharpies seem to bleed so I've got to start carrying a pencil with me as well. Ugh. My camera bag is quickly becoming a toolbox! I brought my SX-70 on the last D&S Photowalk - bigged pain in the butt than I expected. That said, with one exception, the 'Roids turned out very well. Speaking of the Drink & Shoot, the next one is in Dogpatch in September.

description._content: freewikileaks.eu/en/protests/ www.bradleymanning.org Video of Rainey Reitman of EFF www.youtube.com/watch?v=tEeU667tsfA The Best of Cablegate: Instances Where Public Discourse Benefited from the Leaks by Rainey Reitman www.eff.org/deeplinks/2011/01/cablegate-disclosures-have-... Description of event www.facebook.com/event.php?eid=178950392136750 "Since its release of about 2000 diplomatic cables (as of January 7th, 2011), Wikileaks has been subject to extraordinary pressures, seemingly at the behest of the US government. Amazon and EveryDNS have denied Wikileaks internet service and Visa, Mastercard, Paypal, and Bank of America have been prevented supporters from donating money to Wikileaks. This is despite the fact that Wikileaks has not even been charged with a crime. Unfortunately, the situation has gotten even worse. The press has been spreading lies about Wikileaks. Mainstream media outlets do not appear to be doing even the most rudimentary fact-checking. The most blatant of these lies is the idea that Wikileaks has “indiscriminately dumped 250,000 cables on the internet”. This is flat-out false. A few news organizations, including NPR and InformationWeek, have corrected this mistake, and NPR has even offered an apology. By contrast, most news organizations ranging from the AP to the Wall Street Journal continue to print this falsehood. We call upon all news organizations to correct previous articles and statements, to issue apologies to their readers, and to take steps to prevent this mistake from occurring in any future articles and shows. We will be protesting outside the TransAmerica pyramid, across from a San Francisco office of the New York Times, on Saturday, January 15th, at 4pm. On that day, we will be joining in protesting against the repression of Wikileaks with many others around the world, including Washington, DC, and several cities in Canada and Australia. To counter the New York Times’s censorship of reality, we plan to publish the released cables on the walls of their building. In addition, participants will be provided cable printouts and markers and encouraged to throw down their artistic abilities by adding a graphic representation of their favorite cable to the Cablegate Coloring Book. References: [1] 8 Smears and Misconceptions About WikiLeaks Spread By the Media www.alternet.org/story/149369/8_smears_and_misconceptions... photo.title: San Francisco Skyline - Christmas Eve 2010

description._content: San Francisco Skyline on Christmas Eve of 2010. Shot from Treasure Island with Nikon D7000 and Sigma 70-200mm f/2.8 Here is a link to zoomable gigapan version of this image: gigapan.org/gigapans/67653/ This is a composite of 33 shots. Each shot is 10 seconds exposure at F4. It was a little windy night and not everything as sharp as I wanted to be. There are many lens flare artifacts (I forgot to take off UV filter off the lens) Final cropped image came out to 39347x4594 pixels = 180 Megapixels. I had to re-size it to 30000 pixels wide to output it in JPG (I think this is a Photoshop Limitation) If printed at 300dpi it would make a print about and 130 inches wide x 15 inches high . (0.4 x 3.3 meters) Enjoy and feel free to leave me comments. Thanks.

description._content: The Transamerica Pyramid is the tallest and most iconic skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline. It originally housed the headquarters of the Transamerica Corporation. It was designed by architect William Pereira and constructed 1969-1972. It it is 260 m (850 ft) tall and was one of the tallest buildings in the world when it opened. The building is a tall, four-sided pyramid with two "wings" on either side to accommodate an elevator shaft on the east and a stairwell and a smoke tower on the west.

description._content:
Courtesy of Wiki: 

The Transamerica Pyramid - designed by architect William Pereira, at 260 m (850 ft), upon completion it was among the five tallest buildings in the world.  The tower no longer serves as the Transamerica Corporation headquarters; the building is evocative of San Francisco and has become one of the many symbols of the city.  It faced considerable opposition during its planning and construction, and was sometimes referred to by detractors as "Pereira's Prick".

**From what I recall this street was just one block over from Chinatown... I could be wrong though.  After a while those city streets began to blend together.  As a tourist there comes a time when enough is enough; the crowds become annoying rather than intriguing and fun and the inspiration for a great photo is few and far between.  This image was captured at that point for me. 

Please do not misunderstand, I had a wonderful time in San Francisco, but I'm more of a vast landscape/nature kind of girl and on this trip we really did not get the opportunities to hunt for those vast landscapes/nature-filled areas the way I had hoped.  

I would like to go back, but next time I'm renting a vehicle.  I want to be able to hit the open road and do a little exploration.  :)

My scanner can be really uncooperative at times. I did kind of a crap job at scanning it (it's not actually that icky yellow tone. I'm so lazy.), but in the end, I love this 'Roid.

I need to buy a new one anyway. I'm thinking one of those multipurpose flatbed/neg scanners. I realize that the negative scans won't turn out as well as a dedicated negative scanner's scans would, but my technique for 120 neg scanning was killed by the demise of one scanner, so I need to be able to do that somehow. Anyone have any scanner recommendations? (I have more 120 negs sitting around - just waiting to be scanned - than I'd like. And also I'm pretty sure I didn't need to type the word "scan" and its various forms that many times.) 

Who loves dive bars? I do! Yay Mr. Bing's. There were just so many photogs in there. It was kind of hilarious. That last D&S was kind of more massive than I expected. Not a bad thing, just unexpected. 

Also? Whole first page of my stream? Instant film. Yay buddy.

description._content:
The changing light
                 at San Francisco
       is none of your East Coast light
                none of your
                            pearly light of Paris
The light of San Francisco
                        is a sea light
                                       an island light
And the light of fog
                   blanketing the hills
          drifting in at night
                      through the Golden Gate
                                       to lie on the city at dawn
And then the halcyon late mornings
       after the fog burns off
            and the sun paints white houses
                                    with the sea light of Greece
                 with sharp clean shadows
                       making the town look like
                                it had just been painted

But the wind comes up at four o'clock
                                     sweeping the hills

And then the veil of light of early evening

And then another scrim
                  when the new night fog
                                        floats in
And in that vale of light
                      the city drifts
                                    anchorless upon the ocean

- Lawrence Ferlinghetti - "The Changing Light"

photo.title: Fifth Alarm

description._content: This is the view from the other side of the Parking Garage. Below is the intersection of Chinatown and Little Italy. This side isn't nearly as dense, but contains some of the most recognizable sights of San Francisco - the Bay Bridge and the Transamerica Pyramid. Tomorrow is the Inaugural Firefighter Stair Climb up the iconic Transamerica Pyramid. Firefighters, police, military personnel and fitness enthusiasts will climb the Transamerica Pyramid to benefit the Bothin Burn Center, the Alisa Ann Ruch Burn Foundation and the San Francisco Firefighters’ Toy Program. Participants will run up 48 flights of stairs in 50 pounds of gear. It is a regular day for firefighters — but Saturday, it will be for charity. Read more at the San Francisco Examiner: SF Firefighter Stair Climb and at Fifth Alarm. Fluidr
